EDA Breast Cancer Proteomes: Dividing breast cancer patients into separate sub-classes

Wytze Bekker

9/21/2020

Introduction

This project is based on the publication Mertins, P., Mani, D., Ruggles, K. et al. Proteogenomics connects somatic mutations to signalling in breast cancer. Nature 534, 55-62 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1038/nature18003

From this publication, we can obtain 3 files:
77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv, which contains log2 normalized expression values for several proteins from 80 breast cancer patients and 3 healthy individuals. The proteins are named with full names and symbols, but also with the RefSeq accession numbers so we can refer to the refseq database.

clinical_data_breast_cancer.csv, where we can find data about the cancer classification. It also contains information about several of the patiens also in 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv, so we can combine these two datasets.

PAM50_proteins.csv contains the list of genes and proteins used by the PAM50 classification system. This one as well we can link to 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv using the RefSeq accession numbers. We will not be using this file in this EDA, but might use it furtheron in the research.

The main target in this EDA is to remove some unuseful data and combine 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv and clinicaldatabreast_cancer.csv to create one bigger dataset containing more data, which we can then use to answer our research question: Using machinelearning, can we predict/determine the subclass of breastcancer based on the patients protein expression values?

Codebooks

A description of most rows/columns in the datasets we use.
Codebook for clinical_data_breast_cancer.csv:

1 Complete TCGA ID Matches the names in 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv

21 PAM50 mRNA
22 SigClust Unsupervised mRNA
23 SigClust Intrinsic mRNA
24 miRNA Clusters
25 methylation Clusters
26 RPPA Clusters
27 CN Clusters

30 Integrated Clusters (unsup exp)
Codebook for 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv:
Number Column Description
1 RefSeqaccessionnumber RefSeq protein ID, refers to the RefSeq database
2 gene_symbol A symbol unique to each gene
3 gene_name A full name of the gene
4 Remaining columns Log2 iTRAQ protein expression ratios for each sample, three last columns are from healthy individuals

We take a look at the dimensions before and after crudely omitting all NAs

## [1] 12553    86
## [1] 6912   86

Omitting all NAs removes roughly half of the data, this means theres a lot of NAs, but just simply removing all of them is too much, so we will try to still remove some but not so much. Working with this data will be easier if the table is transformed a bit.

We transpose the data so later on we can more easily combine it with the data from clinical_data_breast_cancer.csv, because both will have theComplete.TCGA.ID" as row names, which is the patient identifier code.

##Take the RefSeq_accesstion_numbers so we can add those as columnnames
names <- data77$RefSeq_accession_number
##Transpose the data and readd the RefSeq_accession_number
data77.transp <- as.data.frame(t(data77[,4:86]))
colnames(data77.transp) <- names

##Add the Complete.TCGA.ID column
data77.transp <- cbind(rownames(data77.transp), data.frame(data77.transp, row.names = NULL))
colnames(data77.transp)[1] <- "Complete.TCGA.ID"

The values of Complete.TCGA.id refer to values in clinical_data_breast_cancer.csv, but are formatted differently, but we will now change them to be the same

##Function to convert the TCGA id's to the correct format
get.clinical.id <- function(proteome.id) {
  x = substr(proteome.id, 4, 7)
  y = substr(proteome.id, 0, 2)
  paste("TCGA",y,x,sep="-")
}

##Use sapply to get the correctly formatted Complete.TCGA.ID column in data77.transp
data77.transp$Complete.TCGA.ID <- sapply(data77.transp$Complete.TCGA.ID, get.clinical.id)

We can now see how the NAs are distributed. Most proteins have no NAs so we will not include these in the plot.

##Count the amount of NA's per protein(column)
na_count <- sapply(data77.transp, function(y) sum(length(which(is.na(y)))))
na_count <- data.frame(na_count)

##Create a plot to show the distribution of NA's
na_count <- na_count[(na_count$na_count > 0),]
na_count <- data.frame(na_count)
ggplot(na_count, aes(na_count)) + geom_bar() +xlab("Number of NA's") + ylab("Occurences") +ggtitle("Figure 1: Distribution of NA's")

In figure 1 we can see there are a lot of proteins with 1-10 NAs, but there is not a lot of difference in amounts of NAs in the range 10-55. We will have to decide on a cutoff value for the amount of NAs. This will be more than 20 NAs, which, with a total of 80, equals 25%.

##Remove proteins(columns) with more than 25%(=20) NA's
data77.filt <- data77.transp[,(colMeans(is.na(data77.transp))<0.25)]

We can see we have removed about 2200 proteins, which all contained too much NAs.

Now we combine the modified data from 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv with the data from clinical_data_breast_cancer.csv.

##Combine the two datasets
data.merged <- inner_join(data_clin, data77.filt, by = "Complete.TCGA.ID")
We now have one big table containing data from both 77_cancer_proteomes_CPTAC_itraq.csv and clinicaldatabreast_cancer.csv and removed several columns we deemed unusefull due to too many NAs. We show a sample of some columns.

Usability

In figure 2 we can see that even with this big a dataset, there is still a lot of variety in the expression values. There are a lot of outliers, which might prove useful during machine learning.

In figure 3 we can see several lighter lines, indicating that some genes have lower correlation with other genes. Considering this is a random selection, we can assume all of the data has similar levels/distribution in correlation. This means we can use these with machine learning to find patterns.

In figure 4 we can see for example that for the randomly chosen NP_061198 expression in Basal-like and HER2-enriched tumors is generally slightly below average.

In figure 5 we can see a relatively big spike in Basal-like tumors, which could be a nice classifier for machine learning.

In figure 6 we can see that NP_001025062 is differently expressed in Luminal A tumors, yet again a possible handhold for machinelearning.

This data seems usable for subtyping via machine learning because even when randomly selecting a few attributes to compare, we can see clear differences in expression.

Conclusion

This data is usable for subtyping via machine learning because even when randomly selecting a few attributes to compare, we can see clear differences in expression. The data has been partially cleaned from NAs, and combined into 1 dataset to use for machine learning.
